1. Types of Relationships

a. One-to-One
Definition:
Each entity instance is related to exactly one instance of another entity.

Example:
A User has one Profile.

@Entity
public class User {
    @Id @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    @OneToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "profile_id") // Foreign key in User table
    private Profile profile;
}

@Entity
public class Profile {
    @Id @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;
    private String bio;
}
@OneToOne defines the relationship.
@JoinColumn specifies the foreign key column.

b. One-to-Many / Many-to-One

Definition:
One-to-Many: One entity is related to many instances of another entity.
Many-to-One: Many entities relate to one instance of another entity.

Example:
A User has many Posts. Each Post belongs to one User.

@Entity
public class User {
    @Id @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "user", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
    private List<Post> posts = new ArrayList<>();
}

@Entity
public class Post {
    @Id @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "user_id") // Foreign key in Post table
    private User user;
}

@OneToMany(mappedBy = "user") means the user field in Post owns the relationship.
@ManyToOne is placed on the owning side (the table with the foreign key).

c. Many-to-Many

Definition:
Each entity instance can relate to many instances of another entity, and vice versa.

Example:
A Student can enroll in many Courses, and a Course can have many Students.

@Entity
public class Student {
    @Id @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    @ManyToMany
    @JoinTable(
        name = "student_course",
        joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "student_id"),
        inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "course_id")
    )
    private Set<Course> courses = new HashSet<>();
}

@Entity
public class Course {
    @Id @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    @ManyToMany(mappedBy = "courses")
    private Set<Student> students = new HashSet<>();
}

@JoinTable defines the join table and its columns.

What is inverseJoinColumns?

In a @ManyToMany relationship, a join table is used to link the two entities (e.g.,
student_course links Student and Course).
The @JoinTable annotation defines the join table and its columns.
joinColumns specifies the foreign key column(s) that reference the current entity
(the owner).
inverseJoinColumns specifies the foreign key column(s) that reference the other entity
(the inverse side).

Info:
student_id is a foreign key to the Student table.
course_id is a foreign key to the Course table.
The join table (student_course) will look like:

student_id	                                              course_id

1	                                                      2
1	                                                      3
2	                                                      2

Why do we use inverseJoinColumns?

Clarity: It clearly defines which column in the join table points to which entity.
Correct Mapping: Ensures JPA/Hibernate knows how to join the tables when fetching or saving
data.
Bidirectional Relationships: When both entities reference each other, inverseJoinColumns
helps maintain the correct mapping from both sides.

Benefits:

Explicit Mapping:
You control the names of the join table and its columns, which is important for database
design, readability, and integration with existing schemas.

Avoids Ambiguity:
Without inverseJoinColumns, JPA might not know which column refers to which entity,
especially in bidirectional relationships.

Database Consistency:
Ensures foreign keys are set up correctly, maintaining referential integrity.

What does joinColumns mean in @JoinTable?
In a @ManyToMany relationship, a join table (e.g., student_course) is created to connect the
two entities (Student and Course).

The join table has two foreign keys:
One referencing the primary key of the owning entity (Student)
One referencing the primary key of the inverse entity (Course)

joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "student_id")
This means the student_id column in the student_course table is a foreign key that refers to
the id column (primary key) in the Student table.

inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "course_id")
This means the course_id column in the student_course table is a foreign key that refers to
the id column (primary key) in the Course table.

Student Table
-------------
id | name
1  | Alice
2  | Bob

Course Table
------------
id | title
2  | Math
3  | Science

student_course (Join Table)
---------------------------
student_id | course_id
1          | 2
1          | 3
2          | 2

How is the Join Table Created?

1. Automatic Table Creation by JPA/Hibernate
When you define a @ManyToMany relationship in your entity classes and use the @JoinTable
annotation, JPA/Hibernate automatically creates the join table in the database for you—even
if you don’t explicitly create it in your SQL scripts.

You do not need to manually write SQL to create the join table.
The table is created based on your entity annotations when you run your application and have
spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=update (or create, create-drop) in your configuration.


How is the Join Table Created?
1. Automatic Table Creation by JPA/Hibernate

When you define a @ManyToMany relationship in your entity classes and use the @JoinTable
annotation, JPA/Hibernate automatically creates the join table in the database for you—even
if you don’t explicitly create it in your SQL scripts.

You do not need to manually write SQL to create the join table.
The table is created based on your entity annotations when you run your application and have
spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=update (or create, create-drop) in your configuration.

2. What Does @JoinTable Do?

@JoinTable tells JPA/Hibernate:
The name of the join table (e.g., student_course)
The columns that act as foreign keys (student_id, course_id)
JPA uses this information to generate the join table schema.

Both columns are foreign keys referencing the primary keys of the Student and Course tables.
3. What if You Don’t Use @JoinTable?
If you omit @JoinTable, JPA will still create a join table for a @ManyToMany relationship,
but it will use default names (usually combining the entity names and their primary keys).

4. Configuration Required
For automatic table creation, make sure your application.properties or application.yml
includes:

properties

spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=update

or

spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=create

This tells Hibernate to generate (or update) the database schema based on your entity classes.


